Creating new variables needed for following analyses.

dt <- dt %>% 
  mutate(info_seek_doc = case_when(
    Info_seeking_3 == "1" ~ "No",
    Info_seeking_3 == "2" ~ "No",
    Info_seeking_3 == "3" ~ "Yes",
    Info_seeking_3 == "4" ~ "Yes"
  ),
  info_seek_interpersonal = case_when(
    Info_seeking_4 == "1" ~ "No",
    Info_seeking_4 == "2" ~ "No",
    Info_seeking_4 == "3" ~ "Yes",
    Info_seeking_4 == "4" ~ "Yes"
  ),
  info_seek_media = case_when(
    Info_seeking_1 == "1" ~ "No",
    Info_seeking_2 == "2" ~ "No",
    Info_seeking_3 == "3" ~ "Yes",
    Info_seeking_4 == "4" ~ "Yes"
  ),
  gender = case_when(
    Gender == "2" ~ "Woman",
    Gender == "1" ~ "Man",
    Gender == "3" ~ "Woman",
  ),
  rural_urban = case_when(
    ruca_rural == "rural" ~ "Rural",
    ruca_rural == "not_rural" ~ "Urban"
  ),
  edu = case_when(
    Education == "1" ~ "less than college",
    Education == "2" ~ "less than college",
    Education == "3" ~ "less than college",
    Education == "4" ~ "college",
    Education == "5" ~ "college",
    Education == "6" ~ "graduate",
    Education == "7" ~ "graduate",
    Education == "8" ~ "graduate",
  ))

Created a new summary dataset that groups the original dataset.

A.) “count”: is the number of participants following into four categories formed by crossing “rural_urban” (Rural vs. Urban) with “info_seek_doc” (Yes vs. No).

B.) “frequency”: uses the “count” variable to calculate the relative proportion for each response category to “info_seek_doc”, still grouped by “rural_urban”.

C.) “percent”: rounds the results of “frequency” to the nearest percentage point. “percent” records an integer.

dt_rural_info <- dt %>%
  group_by(rural_urban, info_seek_doc) %>%
  summarize(N = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  mutate(freq = N/sum(N),
         pct = round((freq*100), 0))

dt_rural_info %>%
  group_by(rural_urban) %>%
  summarize(total=sum(pct))

Bar graph from the new summary dataset.

p_q1b <- ggplot(dt_rural_info, 
            aes(x = rural_urban, y = pct, fill = info_seek_doc))

p_q1b + geom_col(position = "dodge2") + 
labs(x = "Rural or Urban", y = "Percent", fill = "Seeking COVID-19 Information from Doctors") +
theme(legend.position = "top")

In urban areas, the likelihood of seeking out COVID-19 related information is 50%, while the other 50% are not likely to seek out information. In rural areas, people are less likely to seek COVID-19 related information than in urban areas.

Summary dataset that groups the original dataset that now incorporates gender.

dt_rural_gender_info <- dt %>%

The rural_urban differences in the likelihood of seeking COVID-19 information has the same conclusion as before with those living in urban areas less likely to seek information. When looking at the differences for men vs women in rural and urban areas, men are more likely to seek information, while women are 20% less likely to seek information.

Dataset describing people’s beliefs about COVID-19.

“mis_covid_overall” is made up of the beliefs below:

Mis_covid_health_2_1: Wearing face masks can cause carbon dioxide toxicity and hence can weaken immune system. Mis_covid_health_2_2: Many countries have reached the standard for herd immunity. Mis_covid_health_2_3: Thermal scanners can detect COVID-19. Mis_covid_health_2_4: Ultra-violet (UV) lamps can be used to disinfect and are safe for humans and pets. Mis_covid_health_2_5: Hydroxychloroquine is effective in curing COVID-19. Mis_covid_health_2_6: A coronavirus vaccine used on dogs or bovine can be used to prevent COVID-19 on people. Mis_covid_health_2_7: Chlorine dioxide kits sold online under various “MMS” names — Miracle Mineral Solution, Miracle Mineral Supplement, Master Mineral Solution — will cure the coronavirus. Mis_covid_health_2_8: Only N95 masks can prevent the spread of COVID. Mis_covid_health_2_9: Sunlight actually can kill the novel coronavirus. Mis_covid_health_2_10: Drinking alcohol beverages can help prevent COVID-19.

Participants were asked to report their level of agreement on a 5-point scale (1 = strongly disagree, 5 = strongly agree).

“social_media_skepticism” = (“Sm_skepticism_27” + “Sm_skepticism_28”)/2 Sm_skepticism_27: Too often, credible news information is mixed up with misinformation on social media. Sm_skepticism_28: You can’t trust the news stories people share on social media.

Participants were asked to report their level of agreement on a 5-point scale (1 = strongly disagree, 5 = strongly agree).

“conspiracy” = (“gen_consprcy_belief_1” + “gen_consprcy_belief_2” +…+ “gen_consprcy_belief_5”)/5 gen_consprcy_belief_1: I think that many very important things happen in the world, which the public is never informed about. gen_consprcy_belief_2: I think that politicians usually do not tell us the true motives for their decisions. gen_consprcy_belief_3: I think that government agencies closely monitor all citizens. gen_consprcy_belief_4: I think that events which superficially seem to lack a connection are often the result of secret activities. gen_consprcy_belief_5: I think that there are secret organizations that greatly influence political decisions.

Participants were asked to report how likely they think each statement is true on a 7-point scale (1 = certainly not, 7 = certain).

“nationalism” = (“Nationalism_1” + “Nationalism_2” + …+ “Nationalism_4”)/4 Nationalism_1: I would rather be a citizen of my country than of any other country. Nationalism_2: The world would be a better place if people from other countries were more like my country. Nationalism_3: My country is a better country than most other countries. Nationalism_4: It makes me proud when my country does well in international sports.

Participants were asked to report their level of agreement on a 5-point scale (1 = strongly disagree, 5 = strongly agree).

“trust_scientists” = “Institutional_trust_5” (converted to numeric) Institutional_trust_5: The Scientific Community

Participants were asked to rate how much trust they have in the institution on a 0-100 scale.

“trust_press” = “Institutional_trust_6” (converted to numeric) Institutional_trust_6: The Press

Participants were asked to rate how much trust they have in the institution on a 0-100 scale.

“trust_medical” = “Institutional_trust_11” (converted to numeric) Institutional_trust_11: The Medical Community

Participants were asked to rate how much trust they have in the institution on a 0-100 scale.

“religiosity” = “religiosity_2” (converted to numeric) religiosity_2: How often do you go to religious services?

Participants responded on a 5-point scale, ranging from 1 = never to 5 = every week.

“age” = “age” (converted to numeric)

dt_ols_corr <- dt %>%
  mutate(Mis_covid_health_2_1 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_1), 
         Mis_covid_health_2_2 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_2),

         Mis_covid_health_2_4 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_4),
         Mis_covid_health_2_5 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_5), 
         Mis_covid_health_2_6 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_6), 
         Mis_covid_health_2_7 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_7), 
         Mis_covid_health_2_8 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_8), 
         Mis_covid_health_2_9 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_9), 
         Mis_covid_health_2_10 = as.numeric(Mis_covid_health_2_10), 
         Sm_skepticism_27 = as.numeric(Sm_skepticism_27), 
         Sm_skepticism_28 = as.numeric(Sm_skepticism_28), 
         gen_consprcy_belief_1 = as.numeric(gen_consprcy_belief_1), 
         gen_consprcy_belief_2 = as.numeric(gen_consprcy_belief_2), 
         gen_consprcy_belief_3 = as.numeric(gen_consprcy_belief_3), 
         gen_consprcy_belief_4 = as.numeric(gen_consprcy_belief_4), 
         gen_consprcy_belief_5 = as.numeric(gen_consprcy_belief_5), 
         Nationalism_1 = as.numeric(Nationalism_1), 
         Nationalism_2 = as.numeric(Nationalism_2), 
         Nationalism_3 = as.numeric(Nationalism_3), 
         Nationalism_4 = as.numeric(Nationalism_4), 
         Institutional_trust_5 = as.numeric(Institutional_trust_5), 
         Institutional_trust_6 = as.numeric(Institutional_trust_6), 
         Institutional_trust_11 = as.numeric(Institutional_trust_11), 
         religiosity_2 = as.numeric(religiosity_2), 
         age = as.numeric(age), 
         mis_covid_overall = (Mis_covid_health_2_1 + Mis_covid_health_2_2 + 
                                Mis_covid_health_2_3 + Mis_covid_health_2_4 + 
                                Mis_covid_health_2_5 + Mis_covid_health_2_6 +
                                Mis_covid_health_2_7 + Mis_covid_health_2_8 +
                                Mis_covid_health_2_9 + Mis_covid_health_2_10)/10,
         social_media_skepticism = (Sm_skepticism_27 + Sm_skepticism_28)/2, 
         conspiracy = (gen_consprcy_belief_1 + gen_consprcy_belief_2 + 
                         gen_consprcy_belief_3 + gen_consprcy_belief_4 + 
                         gen_consprcy_belief_5)/5, 
         nationalism = (Nationalism_1 + Nationalism_2 + 
                          Nationalism_3 + Nationalism_4)/4, 
         trust_scientists = Institutional_trust_5, 
         trust_press = Institutional_trust_6, 
         trust_medical = Institutional_trust_11, 
         religiosity = religiosity_2, age = age) %>%
  select(mis_covid_overall, social_media_skepticism, conspiracy, 
         nationalism, trust_scientists, trust_press, trust_medical, 
         religiosity, age)

New dataset called “dt_ols”

Made up of the variables in “dt_ols_corr”, plus “rural_urban”, “gender”, and “edu” from dt.

dt_ols <- dt %>%
  mutate(mis_covid_overall = dt_ols_corr$mis_covid_overall,
         social_media_skepticism = dt_ols_corr$social_media_skepticism,
         conspiracy = dt_ols_corr$conspiracy,
         nationalism = dt_ols_corr$nationalism,
         trust_scientists = dt_ols_corr$trust_scientists,
         trust_press = dt_ols_corr$trust_press,
         trust_medical = dt_ols_corr$trust_medical,
         religiosity = dt_ols_corr$religiosity,
         age = dt_ols_corr$age) %>%
  select(mis_covid_overall,social_media_skepticism,conspiracy,
         nationalism,trust_scientists,trust_press,trust_medical,
         religiosity,age,rural_urban,gender,edu)

dt_ols

Multiple regression model

Using “mis_covid_overall” as the outcome variable (DV), and the following as the independent variables:

social_media_skepticism conspiracy nationalism trust_scientists trust_press trust_medical religiosity rural_urban age gender edu

ols <- lm(formula = mis_covid_overall ~ social_media_skepticism + conspiracy +
          nationalism + trust_scientists + trust_press + trust_medical + religiosity + 
          rural_urban + age + gender + edu,
          data = dt_ols)

summary(ols)

All the significant independent variables: conspiracy, nationalism, religiosity, age,and genderWoman.

Estimated regression coefficient for “conspiracy” and statistical significance: For “conspiracy”, the estimated regression coefficient is 0.2505380. It is statistically significant because its p value is smaller than 0.05. If one increases or decreases the “conspiracy” by one unit, the outcome will correspondingly increases or decreases by 0.2505380.

Estimated regression coefficient for “gender_Woman” and its statistical significance: For “gender_Woman”, the estimated regression coefficient is -0.2627436. It is statistically significant because its p value is smaller than 0.05. Compared with participants who are male, “mis_covid_overall” was 0.2627436 units lower in participants who are female.

Model outputs into a tidy data frame, with the addition of 95% confidence intervals for all the regression coefficients to the tidy output. It is called “out_conf”.

library(broom)

out_conf <- tidy(ols)

out_conf

Figure to visually summarize the estimated regression coefficients and 95% confidence intervals.

library(socviz)

out_conf <- tidy(ols, conf.int = TRUE)
out_conf
out_conf <- subset(out_conf, 
                   term %nin% "(Intercept)")

p <- ggplot(out_conf, 
            mapping = aes(x = reorder(term, estimate),
                          y = estimate, 
                          ymin = conf.low, 
                          ymax = conf.high))

p + geom_pointrange() + 
  coord_flip() + 
  labs(x="", y="Estimate") + 
  theme_bw()
